CONDOLENCES: Expresses the condolences of the House of Representatives on the death
of Clarence Durham, the last living LaSalle Parish World War II veteran
1 A RESOLUTION
2 To express the condolences of the House of Representatives on the death of Clarence
3 Durham, the last living LaSalle Parish World War II veteran.
4 WHEREAS, it is with immense sadness and profound regret that the House of
5 Representatives of the Legislature of Louisiana has learned of the passing, on March 18,
6 2026, of Clarence Durham, the last living LaSalle Parish World War II veteran; and
7 WHEREAS, Clarence Durham was born on August 16, 1927, during the height of
8 the Great Depression; he was the seventh-born child in his family, and he learned the value
9 of hard work at an early age; he left school after fifth grade to support his family and carried
10 his responsibilities with strength and humility; and
11 WHEREAS, Mr. Durham joined the military at the age of seventeen and served in
12 the United States Merchant Marine; he was sent to Okinawa Island, where he and forty crew
13 members were assigned to transport supplies, including ammunition, guns, and oil, to troops
14 stationed and fighting in Japan and other parts of the world; and
15 WHEREAS, Mr. Durham married the love of his life, Beverly Hunt, after returning
16 from the war; they shared sixty-two years of love and commitment to each other and raised
17 three sons, Gerald, Robert, and Brian; and
18 WHEREAS, Mr. Durham spent forty years in the oil industry and worked on drilling
19 rigs across many different towns and states; he lived in Abbeville, Louisiana, during this
20 time and eventually settled in Jena, Louisiana, in 1971; and
